column25: The evaluation script was able to compile your submission into the
executable pa2.
If there is an attachment CE_log.txt, it means that there were warning
messages from the compiler.  You should pay attention to all the warning
messages to make sure that it is indeed your intention to program in such a
way that you have these warnings.   If your work does not work as intended
(see the feedback included in the attached grade_log.csv), fixing these
warnings may sometimes eliminate these unpredictable behaviors.
The attached grade_log.csv should be viewed as a spreadsheet.  There are
two sets of evaluation.
The first is to evaluate pa2 when all proper arguments are presented to the
executable.  It evaluates the correctness of the output files produced by pa2.
The first column contains the names of the test cases.  The remaining
columns are as follows:
timeout: 0 if your program completed its execution within the time limit
1 otherwise
time(sec): the run time of your program
distinct char: the number of distinct characters in a correctly decoded file
num char: the number of characters in a correctly decoded file
tree file: valid tree file format, -1: file not present
0: format invalid
1: valid file
tree diff: the number of characters in the tree file that do not match
the expected output, 0 is good
maximum is typically 3*dist_char - 1, but if the student outputs
a much larger tree file, could be higher than that.
decoded file: -1: file not present
0: the compressed file has issue (should not happen)
1: decoded file present
decoded diff: the number of characters in the decoded file that do not match
the expected output, 0 is good
maximum is typically num_char, but if the student outputs
a much larger decoded file, could be higher than that.
count file: valid count file format, -1: file not present
0: format invalid
1: valid file
count diff: number of different counts, 0 is good
maximum is 256.
htree file: valid huffman tree file format, -1: file not present
0: format invalid
1: valid file
valid htree: contains all distinct characters in decoded file: 1;
0 otherwise
opt htree: a tree optimally built for Huffman coding: 1;
0 otherwise
eval file: valid eval file format, -1: file not present
0: format invalid
1: valid file
eval diff: the number of differences in the eval file vs the expected one
(based on the input encoded file and "Huffman" tree provided by
the student), 0 is good
maximum is 4, because there are four numbers in an eval file
golden diff: the number of differences in the eval file vs the golden solution
(based on the input encoded file and an optimal Huffman tree
encoding), 0 is good
maximum is 4, because there are four numbers in an eval file
Used memory (bytes): amount of memory used by your program
-1 when your program timed out, seg fault, or stack overflow
Stack overflow: 0 if no overflow
non-zero (timed out, segmentation fault, or actual overflow)
Memory leak: 0 if no memory leak
non-zero (timed out or actual memory leak)
Memory error: 0 if no memory error
non-zero (timed out or actual memory error)
The second set evaluates how the main function of pa2 handle
processing of arguments.  In particular, it checks how your main function
handles (1) an invalid input filename (the file does not exist),
(2) an output filename that cannot be written into, (3) fewer than
expected number of arguments, and (4) more than expected number of arguments.
timeout: 0 if your program completed its execution within the time limit
1 otherwise
wrong answer: 0 means returns the correct status
other values mean the main function did not handle the testing
properly
Used memory (bytes): amount of memory used by your program
-1 when your program timed out, seg fault, or stack overflow
Stack overflow: 0 if no overflow
non-zero (timed out, segmentation fault, or actual overflow)
Memory leak: 0 if no memory leak
non-zero (timed out or actual memory leak)
Memory error: 0 if no memory error
non-zero (timed out or actual memory error)
